Here is the solution in Julia using the DataFrames.jl package:

```julia
using DataFrames, Query

function audi_filter(df::DataFrame)
    df = @from i in df begin
        @where i.manufacturer == "audi" && (i.model == "a4" || i.model == "a4 quattro")
        @select { :_, AudioType => true }
    end |> DataFrame

    return df
end
```

This function takes a DataFrame `df` as input and uses the `@from`, `@where`, and `@select` macros provided by the Query.jl package to filter down the dataset and create the new column. The `@where` clause is used to specify the conditions for filtering, and the `@select` clause is used to select the columns that will be included in the output DataFrame. 

This function then returns the resulting DataFrame.
